The "Green Deal" European
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
In doing so, it becomes a landmark for the entire world — a guide for the transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda for all to achieve this goal.
Of course, the task awaiting the Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is: an apparent excess of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy; a large number of related subjects, ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
His critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined based on objectives with timelines, and the programs and procedures are tailored to these targets.
Overall, the declared ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to destructive plastic and petrochemical pollution, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to implement a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method for achieving this must rely on citizens themselves.
Again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere噱头让浮想联翩 (lit. "empty daydreaming").   For a more natural English translation: Again, critics will see the announcements of public consultations as mere window dressing for empty promises.
But speak of idle chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has been dealing with protests turning into riots for over a year, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn following a slight increase in metro ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both desperately seek how to organize or structure a public consultation, but retrospectively.
The American adherents of neoliberalism will once again chuckle and claim that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Translating the given French sentence into English:  "Debarking at an airport in the United States means having to deal with elevators, moving walkways, broken shuttle buses, taxis that don't arrive, rail connections that don't exist, highways in such poor condition that they can't be used, replaced by detours."  This translation aims to convey the same meaning and tone as the original French text.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle now costs 8 billion dollars, if not more, and is financed by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and defend the status quo at all costs.
The solutions provided by the market are a joke when policy is subjected to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be, not one subordinate to business interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense, not in a narrowly partisan one).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated industrial policy at its level.
(I recently indicated, in broad terms, what a social democratic Green New Deal strategy would be for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced decarbonized economy, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable, already exist, at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and the sharing economy in transportation or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flows of primary resources.
But for this, it is necessary to overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining assistance, and other public aids.
The European plan justly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as of course other world regions, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production – around 1% to 2% – toward the green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public tenders, research and development, the renewal of industrial equipment, and so on. Funding will come from both the private sector and public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last great challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents approximately 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China accounts for 30% and the United States for 14%.
Even if Europe manages to implement its green pact in its entirety, it will be in vain if other world regions do not join it in its struggle.
Therefore, the European leaders rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the green pact.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China became the world's largest CO2 emitter (though its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if they do not make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must confront the dangers of the unintended cold war launched by the United States.
The hard-line proponents within the government and the Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself, in the face of pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy could make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's sneaky measures to undermine China and instead offers China a clear and positive partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology across Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen or so Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, rallying, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
